{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"92f44fc0-0c98-4b4a-9c2b-cd09f2b902f3","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already in the container)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to speedscope format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips for K8s:**\n\n- Use `kubectl cp` to copy the trace file out of the pod.\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a [sidecar or ephemeral debug container](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace#collect-using-an-ephemeral-container).\n- For very high CPU where `dotnet-trace` adds too much overhead, use **`perf`** (Linux native) instead:\n  ```bash\n  perf record -p <PID> -g -- sleep 30\n  ```\n\n**`--profile cpu-sampling`** is lightweight and usually sufficient for identifying hot paths.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"48f95c08-f907-40a7-9d94-78f48db70e97","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question that I can answer from knowledge — no tools needed.","outputTokens":379,"requestId":"C3D0:3A80DA:1CC9BD2:206D0F1:6A07C33F"},"id":"6c29a3e2-0dd2-4012-94a3-5953b5d04e9d","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:07:20.796Z","parentId":"a7010158-6eca-4574-85fb-95b6ab89a1c0"}
